					<section>
						<div>
							<h2>Justification</h2>
						</div>
                        
                            <p>There are increasing demands on researchers to continue refining their data practices, including requirements for data sharing coming from federal and other funders. However, support to appropriately manage and assess data (e.g., for sharing) is nonstandard and inconsistent, often relying on the resources of specific institutions, mentors, or individual experience. This is likely to have a disproportionate impact on scholars doing work with data on sensitive populations or that otherwise require extra care, as well as those scholars from underrepresented backgrounds, without well-resourced institutional affiliations, or who otherwise face structural barriers in their work.</p>
                    
                        <div>
                            <h2>DEIA Implications for the Data Lifecycle</h2>
                        </div>

                    <p>How do considerations around Diversity, Equity, Inclusion and Accessibility ...</p>
      

                    <a href="#" class="image" ><img src="images/Survey_data_lifecycle_graphic.png" alt="Research data lifecycle" /></a>
          
                        <div>
                            <h3>Finding existing data</h3>
                                <p><em>Searching, locating, and accessing data for secondary analysis or reuse.</em></p>
                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Metadata: can help keep people from becoming invisible; implications for systems design, management (erasure vs. hypervisibility)</li>                                            
                                        <li>Access: who has access, openness (equity in access), community decisions around ownership, restricting access</li>
                                        <li>Providing appropriate credit (including authorship), citations to datasets</li>
                                        <li>Terms of use agreements</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                        </div>

                        <div>
                            <h3>Data planning</h3>
                                <p><em>Writing data management plans (DMPs) or setting up processes for any stage of working with data.  For example, Data security protocol for IRB proposals; Study design/population choices; Informed consent design; Designating roles and responsibilities</p></em>
                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Metadata - implications for ontological implicit bias, but importance for description and re-use</li>
                                        <li>IRBs - implications for community-based IRBs (tribal IRB as an example) so that the community itself has a say in whether harm</li>
                                            <ul>
                                                <li>Consent forms</li>
                                                <li>What is the role of IRBs? Who should be providing guidance?</li>
                                            </ul>
                                        <li>Community relationships/agreements - has community contributed to project design, research qâ€™s asked?</li>
                                            <ul>
                                               <li>Being explicit about power, partnerships (how will decisions be made?)</li>
                                            </ul>
                                        <li>DMPs that acknowledge DEIA considerations</li>
                                        <li>Funder requirements</li>  
                                            
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                        </div>
						
